<h2>‚≠ê Circle Color</h2>
<p>
  Change the color of the circle to <code>&quot;orange&quot;</code> in the <code>down</code> event
  handler.
</p>
<p><button class="next-btn">Next</button></p>
<h2>‚≠ê Add a <code>up</code> Event Handler</h2>
<p>
  Add an <code>up</code> event handler to draw a <code>&quot;red&quot;</code> circle with radius
  <code>1</code> at <code>x y</code>.
</p>
<p>Run and test the program. Do you see orange and red circles?</p>
<p><button class="next-btn">Next</button></p>
<h2>‚≠ê Add a <code>move</code> Event Handler</h2>
<p>
  Add an <code>move</code> event handler to draw a <code>&quot;black&quot;</code> line to
  <code>x y</code>.
</p>
<p>Run and test the program. Do you see black lines connecting orange and red circles?</p>
<p><button class="next-btn">Next</button></p>
<h2>‚≠ê Only Paint When Down</h2>
<p>If you're using a touchscreen device, you can skip this step.</p>
<p>
  If you're <em>not</em> on a touchscreen, you might have noticed that lines are drawn even when
  you're not clicking. To fix this, we'll track whether the mouse button is pressed.
</p>
<p>
  Add a global variable <code>d</code> with the value <code>false</code>. In the
  <code>down</code> handler, set <code>d</code> to <code>true</code>. In the
  <code>up</code> handler, set it to <code>false</code>. Only draw a line if <code>d</code> is
  <code>true</code>.
</p>
